  "learnings_before": "- Both valproate and carbamazepine are guideline‑consistent first‑line options for focal seizures in children ≤ 2 years; selection is guided by drug availability, tolerability, and the need for laboratory monitoring.\n- Aromatic AEDs (carbamazepine, lamotrigine, phenytoin) are acceptable for focal epilepsy but must be avoided in any child with a documented drug‑induced rash or hypersensitivity.\n- Before any change of therapy, clinicians must obtain baseline safety labs (ALT/AST < 2 × ULN, platelet count > 150 × 10⁹/L, ammonia within normal limits) and, when feasible, a serum level of the current AED.\n- Dose optimisation is performed first: if the current dose is < 20 mg/kg/day for valproate or < 15 mg/kg/day for carbamazepine and seizure control is suboptimal, the dose should be titrated upward in 25‑50 mg increments every 1–2 weeks before considering drug substitution or adjuncts.\n- Exaggerated startles, feeding difficulty, or increased tone in children with cerebral palsy are not automatically attributed to drug toxicity; they require confirmation (e.g., seizure diary or video‑EEG) before altering the regimen.\n- The decision hierarchy is: (1) confirm seizure‑free status (≥ 6 months) and adherence ≥ 80 %; (2) verify normal safety labs; (3) maintain the current regimen unchanged; (4) if either seizure control or labs are inadequate, proceed to dose optimisation; (5) if optimisation fails, consider switching to valproate (after normal LFTs) or adding levetiracetam as an adjunct.\n- Valproate is stocked in >90 % of district pharmacies at ≈ $0.08 per 100 mg; carbamazepine is similarly stocked at ≈ $0.05 per 100 mg; levetiracetam is 2–3 × more expensive and often unavailable, so it is reserved for documented valproate intolerance or failure.\n- Phenobarbital is reserved for refractory cases or when both valproate and levetiracetam are unavailable; it may be used in spastic cerebral palsy only with close monitoring for sedation, otherwise it is avoided.\n- Initiation of valproate requires baseline liver function tests and ammonia; if ALT/AST > 2 × ULN or ammonia is elevated, valproate should be deferred and an alternative AED chosen.\n- When a child is seizure‑free on a stable valproate dose within the therapeutic window (20–30 mg/kg/day) and safety labs are normal, the protocol mandates continuation of the exact current dose without escalation or adjunct addition.",
  "candidate_learnings": "- Carbamazepine is stocked in >90 % of Ugandan district pharmacies at ≈ $0.05 per 100 mg and is the default first‑line AED for focal seizures in school‑age children.  \n- Valproate is used as a second‑line option; it is avoided in females > 2 years when a cheaper effective alternative exists because of teratogenic risk and potential cognitive side‑effects.  \n- Levetiracetam is reserved for cases where carbamazepine is contraindicated, unavailable, or not tolerated, due to its 2–3 × higher price and limited availability.  \n- Phenobarbital is limited to refractory epilepsy or when both carbamazepine and levetiracetam are unavailable, because of sedation risk and poor adherence in school‑aged patients.  \n- Baseline safety labs before starting carbamazepine include CBC, liver enzymes, and serum sodium; routine therapeutic drug monitoring is optional unless seizures persist.  \n- Valproate initiation requires normal CBC, liver function tests, and ammonia; ALT/AST > 2 × ULN or hyperammonemia defers valproate.  \n- Carbamazepine dosing in children: start 10 mg/kg/day divided BID, titrate by 5 mg/kg every 1–2 weeks to a target of 20–30 mg/kg/day, monitoring for rash and hyponatraemia.  \n- Valproate dosing: start 15 mg/kg/day divided BID, titrate to 20–30 mg/kg/day (up to 45 mg/kg/day when seizure control is excellent and serum levels are therapeutic).  \n- Aromatic AEDs (carbamazepine, lamotrigine, phenytoin) are avoided in any child with a documented drug‑induced rash or known HLA‑B*1502 positivity; non‑aromatic alternatives are chosen instead.  \n- When a child is seizure‑free for ≥ 6 months, adherent ≥ 80 %, and labs are normal, the current regimen is maintained unchanged; dose escalation or adjuncts are not indicated.  \n- Dose optimisation is pursued only when seizure control is suboptimal and the current dose is below the therapeutic window (carbamazepine < 15 mg/kg/day, valproate < 20 mg/kg/day).  \n- Polytherapy is introduced only after maximising monotherapy dose; adjunctive agents (e.g., levetiracetam, clobazam) are added only if seizures persist despite therapeutic dosing of the first‑line AED.  \n- For mixed seizure phenotypes (focal plus typical absence), ethosuximide is added to carbamazepine; the two drugs have no significant pharmacokinetic interaction and are both inexpensive and widely stocked.  \n- In resource‑limited settings, any change that increases pill burden or cost is discouraged unless there is clear therapeutic failure or a contraindication.  \n- Reports of poor adherence trigger reinforcement of dosing schedules and counseling before any drug change is considered.  \n- When weight is not recorded, the median weight for age (e.g., 3 y ≈ 12 kg, 7 y ≈ 26 kg, 13 y ≈ 46 kg) is used for dose calculations.",
